            "metadata": {
                "abstract": "Â© 2020 The Author(s). Published by Oxford University Press. All rights reserved.In fields, such as ecology, microbiology and genomics, non-Euclidean distances are widely applied to describe pairwise dissimilarity between samples. Given these pairwise distances, principal coordinates analysis is commonly used to construct a visualization of the data. However, confounding covariates can make patterns related to the scientific question of interest difficult to observe. We provide adjusted principal coordinates analysis as an easy-to-use agent, available as both an R package and a Shiny app, to improve data visualization in this context, enabling enhanced presentation of the effects of interest.",
